AI is the defining technology of our century, transforming everything from national defense and economic growth to healthcare and essential services. In healthcare specifically, AI is driving down costs by streamlining administrative processes and automating tasks like billing, helping eliminate unnecessary paperwork.
 
Today, during a fireside chat with the Cato Institute, I had the opportunity to discuss these impacts, including my successful efforts in repealing the AI diffusion rule and Congress's proposed moratorium on state AI policy. AI must be at the forefront of every leader’s agenda, because it truly is the future!

It was an honor to attend the memorial service for Former President James Earl Carter, Jr. Not only did he serve as the 39th President of the United States, but he also served as the 76th governor of Georgia.

Carter is well known for his philanthropic efforts after his presidency. He was a Nobel Peace Prize winner in 2002 for his tireless efforts to resolve international conflicts and advance democracy and human rights. After his presidency, he founded the Carter Center, a nonpartisan public policy center in Atlanta. Carter also championed Habitat for Humanity, a Georgia-based charity that helps those in need build new homes or renovate older ones.

May he rest in peace.
